{"title_page": "Christian Thompson (artist)", "text_new": "{{About|the Australian artist|other people with the same name|Christian Thompson (disambiguation){{!}}Christian Thompson}}\n{{COI|date=March 2011}}\n{{use Australian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = \n| name          =  Christian Thompson\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|AO}}\n| image         = File:Christian Thompson.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       =  \n| birth_name    = Christian Andrew William Thompson\n| birth_date    = 1978\n| birth_place   = [[Gawler, South Australia]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Australian\n| field         = \n| training      = [[University of Southern Queensland]], [[RMIT University|Royal Melbourne Institute of Technology]], [[University of Oxford]]\n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        =\n|website={{official|https://www.christianthompson.net/}}\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n\n'''Christian Andrew William Thompson''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AO}} (born 1978), also known as '''Christian Bumbarra Thompson''', is an Australian artist.\n\n==Early life, influences and education==\nThompson was born in [[Gawler, South Australia]], north of [[Adelaide]], and trained as an artist in [[Toowoomba, Queensland]]. He is of [[Bidjara (Bulloo River)|Bidjara]] (an [[Aboriginal Australian]] people of central southwestern Queensland) heritage on his father's side, of the [[Bidjara_language|Kunja (Gunya) language group]].<ref >{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson  | website=MGA: the Australian home of photography | url=https://www.mga.org.au/index.php/collection/explore/index/artist/316/image/282/type_chromogenic/1 | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> He also has English, Irish and Scandinavian and [[Sephardic Jewish]] ancestry.<ref name=mga>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson  | website=Monash Gallery of Art: the Australian home of photography | url=https://www.mga.org.au/index.php/collection/explore/index/artist/316/image/282/type_chromogenic/1 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=abc2018/> Thompson's great-great-grandfather is King Billy of Bonny Doon Lorne, a senior tribesman of the Bidjara people who reigned for many years over the district.<ref name=pica>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson: Biography| website=[[Perth Institute of Contemporary Arts]] (PICA) | url=http://www.pica.org.au/__oldsite_2011/view/Christian+Thompson/1361/|date=2010 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThompson had an itinerant childhood, following his father's career in the [[RAAF]],<ref name=mckenzie/> and lived in [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], [[Wagga Wagga]], [[Raymond Terrace]], Toowoomba, and Adelaide, along with his three brothers. He spent his formative years and family holidays in [[Barcaldine, Queensland|Barcaldine]] and in the bush learning the culture and traditions of his father's people from his grandmother and great aunts.<ref name=abc2018>{{cite web | first=Patrick|last= Carey | title=Exhibition charts Christian Thompson's ongoing wanderlust | website=ABC News | date=23 May 2018 | url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-20/christian-thompson-survey-exhibition-ritual-intimacy/9775640 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Many of his family members were creative artists, so he \"grew up surrounded by creative people\". He was greatly encouraged by his art teacher.<ref name=mckenzie/>\n\nHe undertook his [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degree in Toowoomba at the [[University of Southern Queensland]], and in 1999 he relocated to Melbourne to undertake his [[honours degree|Honours]] in Fine Art at the [[RMIT University|Royal Melbourne Institute of Technology]].<ref name=rmit>{{cite web | title=RMIT alumni receive Queen\u2019s Birthday honours | website=RMIT University | date=21 June 2018 | url=https://www.rmit.edu.au/news/all-news/2018/jun/rmit-alumni-receive-queens-birthday-honours | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhile studying at Toowoomba and Melbourne, Thompson was heavily inspired by [[Fluxus]] artists [[George Maciunas]] and [[Yoko Ono]], as well [[Andy Warhol]] and many others. He grew up immersed in music and culture of the 1980s and '90s and identified strongly with [[punk music]].<ref name=mckenzie>{{cite interview | interviewer-last=McKenzie | interviewer-first=Janet | title=Christian Thompson interview: \u2018My work does not need to be read through the optical lens of my race\u2019|first=Christian|last=Thompson | website=Studio International | url=https://www.studiointernational.com/index.php/christian-thompson-australian-indigenous-interview | access-date=15 April 2020|date=10 Nov 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe was an active member of the Melbourne art community, exhibiting his own work and curating group exhibitions. He undertook a curatorial internship at the [[Australian Centre for the Moving Image]], and was on the curatorial group for shows Contemporary Commonwealth at the [[National Gallery of Victoria]] and the Australian Centre for the Moving Image. He established the MHUL Workshop, an annual workshop for young Indigenous artists from across Australia.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 2009 he completed a Masters of Theatre degree at the DasArts, part of the [[Amsterdam School of the Arts]]. In 2010 he transferred to the [[Ruskin School of Art]]<ref name=academia>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson - University of Oxford | website=Academia.edu | date=3 August 2015 | url=https://oxford.academia.edu/ChristianThompson | language=af | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=mckenzie/> at the [[University of Oxford]], after being awarded the [[Charles Perkins (Aboriginal activist)|Charlie Perkins]] Scholarship, to complete his [[doctorate]] (Doctorate of Philosophy (Fine Art)<ref name=academia/>}. He was one of the first two [[Indigenous Australians]] to attend Oxford.<ref name=abc2018/>\n\nHe moved to [[London]] some time after his time at Oxford.<ref name=bbc2015/> He said in 2014 that \"a third of my life experiences and memories [were] attached to Europe\", after his time in [[the Netherlands]] and [[England]], and he had a worldview, which influenced his work. As his mother's family was from [[Bampton, Oxfordshire]],<ref name=bbc2015/> he also grew up surrounded by British television shows, and he looked to England rather than the [[United States]], as many young people of his age did.<ref name=mckenzie/>\n\n==Career==\nThompson meditated on the relationship between form and performance, and his early works focused on the relationship to the human form. He later moved into photography and [[video]] as a means to capture the performative qualities of his textile-based [[sculpture]]s and elaborate costumes.<ref name=agnsw>{{cite web | title=Christian Bumbarra Thompson  | website= [[Art Gallery of NSW]] | date=28 January 2015 | url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/resources/exhibition-kits/embodiment/christian-bumbarra-thompson/ | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThompson established himself in 2002 in the Australian art world with his first series, ''Blaks Palace'', a series of photographs and giant oversized sweaters. Thompson's most notable works include his series ''Emotional Striptease'', ''The Gates of Tambo'' and more recently his series ''Australian Graffiti'', which are held in the collections of the [[National Gallery of Australia]] and the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] and AAMU in [[Utrecht]], the Netherlands. His work deals with the nature of [[identity (social science)|identity]] as an ever-evolving and uncharted terrain, bringing together a variety of seemingly disparate forms and themes. He undertook his first major public art project through the Future Arts Research program at the [[Arizona State University]],<ref>{{cite web | title=F.A.R. (Future Arts Research) Launches at Arizona State University  | date=11 September 2008 | url=https://www.artandeducation.net/announcements/111257/f-a-r-future-arts-research-launches-at-arizona-state-university | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> [[Dartmouth College]], and [[Massey University]] International Art Residency, [[Wellington]], New Zealand.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nHis series of photographs ''Lost Together'' was made in the Netherlands where Thompson undertook a residency program at [[DasArts]] developing his live performance work which brought together his Bidjara and European heritage, combining classical music, traditional rhythms and lyrical narratives into richly textured, lilting and evocative arrangements. His sound based work is concerned with the innate lyricism of his traditional language and the expression of this in contemporary traditional and experimental musical forms. His work has appeared in various national and international publications including [[frieze (magazine)|''Frieze'']], ''Art and Australia'', ''Art Monthly'', ''Realtime'', ''Art Review'', ''Vogue'' magazine and in [[Susan Bright]]'s book ''Auto Focus'' published by [[Thames & Hudson]]. Thompson was also shortlisted and highly commended for the [[Kate Challis RAKA Award]] and in 2011 for the [[Blake Prize for Religious Art|Blake Prize]] and the [[Basil Sellers Art Prize]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Exhibitions and gallery holdings==\nHe has presented his photographs, videos and performance work in numerous solo and group exhibitions nationally and internationally. He was the first Aboriginal studio artist at Gertrude Street Contemporary Art Spaces 2006\u20132007,<ref name=westspace>{{cite web | title=Vote Yes - An Aboriginal Thompson Project: Christian Thompson: 26 May \u2013 10 Jun 2006| website=West Space | url=https://westspace.org.au/exhi/6398/view  | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Melbourne. In 2008 he began international residencies at DasArts Advanced Studies for Performing Arts, [[Amsterdam]], and [[Arizona State University]] in the United States. His work is held in many public and private collections in Australia and overseas, including the [[National Gallery of Australia]], National Gallery of Victoria, [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]], [[Queensland Art Gallery]], the [[Kluge-Ruhe Aboriginal Art Collection]] of the [[University of Virginia]], the Peter Klein Collection ([[Eberdingen]], Germany), Latrobe Regional Gallery ([[Morwell, Victoria|Morwell, Australia]]), Aboriginal Art Museum ([[Utrecht]], the Netherlands), Myer Collection (Melbourne, Australia), City of Melbourne Collection, the [[Patrick Corrigan (businessman)#Australian art and photography|Pat Corrigan Collection]], [[Artbank]], [[Cate Blanchett]] and [[Andrew Upton]] collection and private collections.<ref>[https://www.christianthompson.net/cv Christian Thompson CV]</ref>\n\nHis work was included in the [[Biennale of Sydney#17th Biennale of Sydney (2010)|17th International Biennale of Sydney]] ''The Beauty of Distance - Songs of Survival in a Precarious Age'', curated by David Elliot,{{cn|date=April 2020}} and the 2018 [[Adelaide Biennial of Australian Art]] ''Before and After Science'',<ref>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson | website=2018 Adelaide Biennial of Australian Art | url=http://adelaidebiennial.com.au/2018/artist/christian-thompson/ | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> curated by Sarah Tutton and Charlotte Day. In 2010 he was shortlisted for the [[Art Gallery of Western Australia]] [[Western Australian Indigenous Art Awards|Indigenous Art Award]] along with artists such as [[Makinti Napanangka]], [[Gulumbu Yunupingu]], Judy Watson, Wakartu Cory Surprise and Richard Bell. In 2011 Thompson undertook international residencies at the [[Australia Council for the Arts]] Greene street Studio, New York and the Fonderie Darling Studio, Montreal. His work ''Gamu Mambu'' from the Sydney Biennale was included in a major exhibition of Korean and Australian art at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art Australia]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nThompson's video work ''HEAT 2010'' was included in the [[National Gallery of Australia]]'s 2nd [[National Indigenous Art Triennial]]: ''unDISCLOSED'' in 2012.<ref>{{cite web | title=unDISCLOSED: 2nd National Indigenous Art Triennial | website=National Gallery of Australia  | date=19 September 2010 | url=https://nga.gov.au/exhibition/undisclosed/default.cfm?MnuID=ARTISTS&GALID=6549&viewID=3 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> In 2014 he became the first recipient of the [[Massey University]] international arts residency in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|title=New international arts residency has contemporary focus|url=http://creative.massey.ac.nz/about/news/2014/july/new-international-arts-residency-has-contemporary-focus/|website=[[Massey University]]|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis 2011 video work ''Dhagunyilangu'', meaning brother, employs a British male opera singer to interpret the song written in [[Bidjara language|Bidjara]], one of many [[Aboriginal Australian languages|Aboriginal languages]] which have been lost during colonisation.<ref>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson - Dhagunyilangu | website=Michael Reid | date=27 July 2016 | url=https://michaelreid.com.au/communication/art-tube/christian-thompson-dhagunyilangu/ | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> It was  included in the [[TarraWarra Biennial]] in [[Melbourne]]<ref>{{cite web | title=in the loop sept 5: quick picks & opportunities: tarrawarra biennial 2012: sonic spheres | website=RealTime | date=4 September 2012 | url=https://www.realtime.org.au/in-the-loop-sept-5-quick-picks-opportunities/ | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> as well as the [[Pitt Rivers Museum]] at Oxford University in 2012, as part of the photographic series, ''We Bury Our Own''.<ref name=pitt>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson: We Bury Our Own | website=Pitt Rivers Museum | date=26 June 2012 | url=https://www.prm.ox.ac.uk/event/christian-thompson-we-bury-our-own | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> He said in 2015 that the impact of this series on other artists and academics had been the most rewarding thing for him in his career to date.<ref name=bbc2015/>\n\nHe collaborated with [[James Young (British musician) |James Young]], former collaborator of [[Nico]], and recorded his own version of ''Dhagunyilangu'' and created a [[video]] work of himself singing in Bidjara as part of the [[Massey University]] International Art Residency, [[Wellington, New Zealand]]. The video work titled ''Refuge'' is part of a larger series of works titled ''Eight Limbs'' shown at the [[Te Whare Hera Gallery]], Wellington, in 2014.\n\nIn January 2015, Oxford's [[Trinity College, Oxford|Trinity College]] took down the old paintings in its [[dining room]] for the first time in over 400 years to display an exhibition of Thompson's work.<ref name=bbc2015>{{cite web | last=Sebag-Montefiore | first=Clarissa | title=Indigenous artist forges new path | website=BBC News | date=21 August 2015 | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-33955865 | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first survey of his work, an exhibition called ''Ritual Intimacy'', presented in association with [[Monash University Museum of Art]] (MUMA) and cureated by [[Hetti Perkins]] and [[Charlotte Day (curator)|Charlotte Day]], was mounted at [[UNSW Art & Design]] Galleries in Paddington from May to July 2018.<ref name=\"UNSW Art & Design 2018\">{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson: Ritual Intimacy | website=UNSW Art & Design | date=14 July 2018 | url=https://artdesign.unsw.edu.au/unsw-galleries/christian-thompson-ritual-intimacy | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> after being mounted at MUMA, [[Griffith University Art Museum]] in [[Brisbane]] and the [[Samstag Museum of Art]] in Adelaide.<ref name=abc2018/>\n\nFrom May 2018 he worked on his first [[virtual reality]] project,<ref name=abc2018/> under the [[Australian Centre for the Moving Image]] Mordant Family VR Commission. It was mounted at ACMI in May 2019, titled ''Bayi Gardiya (Singing Desert)''. In the seven-minute installation, Thompson sings in the [[Bidjara language]], which had been lost but is being revived. Thompson is the first recipient of the Mordant Family Commission VR, a three-year program worth {{AUD|240,000}} to support artists who have never worked in VR before.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acmi.net.au/events/christian-thompson-bayi-gardiya-singing-desert/|title=Dr Christian Thompson AO: Bayi Gardiya (Singing Desert)|website=ACMI|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n\nIn 2010, Thompson was awarded the inaugural [[Charles Perkins (Aboriginal activist)|Charlie Perkins]] Scholarship to the [[University of Oxford]] to undertake his Doctorate of Philosophy (Fine Art), and was among the first cohort of Australian Aboriginal people to attend Oxford University in its 900-year history.<ref name=rmit/><ref name=abc2018/>\n\nIn 2018, he was made an Officer in the General Division of the [[Order of Australia]] in the [[2018 Queen's Birthday Honours (Australia)]], for \"outstanding service to the visual arts as a sculptor, photographer, video and performance artist, and as a role model for young Indigenous artists\".<ref name=rmit/>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web | title=Andy and Oz: parallel visions: A collaboration between the National Gallery of Australia and The Andy Warhol Museum, Pittsburgh, USA.| website=National Gallery of Australia  | date=30 December 2007 | url=https://nga.gov.au/andyandoz/index.cfm}}\n*{{cite web | title=Christian Bumbarra Thompson  | website=Art Gallery of NSW | date=28 January 2015 | url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/resources/exhibition-kits/embodiment/christian-bumbarra-thompson/ }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|www.christianthompson.net}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Christian}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian Aboriginal artists]]\n[[Category:Australian contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Australian performance artists]]\n[[Category:Australian photographers]]\n[[Category:Bidjara]]\n[[Category:People from Gawler, South Australia]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Australian artist|other people with the same name|Christian Thompson (disambiguation){{!}}Christian Thompson}}\n{{COI|date=March 2011}}\n{{use Australian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = \n| name          =  Christian Thompson\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=AUS|size=100%|AO}}\n| image         = File:Christian Thompson.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       =  \n| birth_name    = Christian Andrew William Thompson\n| birth_date    = 1978\n| birth_place   = [[Gawler, South Australia]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Australian\n| field         = \n| training      = [[University of Southern Queensland]], [[RMIT University|Royal Melbourne Institute of Technology]], [[University of Oxford]]\n| movement      = \n| works         = \n| patrons       = \n| influenced    = \n| awards        =\n|website={{official|https://www.christianthompson.net/}}\n}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n\n'''Christian Andrew William Thompson''' {{post-nominals|country=AUS|AO}} (born 1978), also known as '''Christian Bumbarra Thompson''', is an Australian artist.\n\n==Early life, influences and education==\nThompson was born in [[Gawler, South Australia]], north of [[Adelaide]], and trained as an artist in [[Toowoomba, Queensland]]. He is of [[Bidjara (Bulloo River)|Bidjara]] (an [[Aboriginal Australian]] people of central southwestern Queensland) heritage on his father's side, of the [[Bidjara_language|Kunja (Gunya) language group]].<ref >{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson  | website=MGA: the Australian home of photography | url=https://www.mga.org.au/index.php/collection/explore/index/artist/316/image/282/type_chromogenic/1 | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> He also has English, Irish and Scandinavian and [[Sephardic Jewish]] ancestry.<ref name=mga>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson  | website=Monash Gallery of Art: the Australian home of photography | url=https://www.mga.org.au/index.php/collection/explore/index/artist/316/image/282/type_chromogenic/1 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=abc2018/> Thompson's great-great-grandfather is King Billy of Bonny Doon Lorne, a senior tribesman of the Bidjara people who reigned for many years over the district.<ref name=pica>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson: Biography| website=[[Perth Institute of Contemporary Arts]] (PICA) | url=http://www.pica.org.au/__oldsite_2011/view/Christian+Thompson/1361/ | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThompson had an itinerant childhood, following his father's career in the [[RAAF]],<ref name=mckenzie/> and lived in [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], [[Wagga Wagga]], [[Raymond Terrace]], Toowoomba, and Adelaide, along with his three brothers. He spent his formative years and family holidays in [[Barcaldine, Queensland|Barcaldine]] and in the bush learning the culture and traditions of his father's people from his grandmother and great aunts.<ref name=abc2018>{{cite web | first=Patrick|last= Carey | title=Exhibition charts Christian Thompson's ongoing wanderlust | website=ABC News | date=23 May 2018 | url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-05-20/christian-thompson-survey-exhibition-ritual-intimacy/9775640 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Many of his family members were creative artists, so he \"grew up surrounded by creative people\". He was greatly encouraged by his art teacher.<ref name=mckenzie/>\n\nHe undertook his [[Bachelor of Fine Arts]] degree in Toowoomba at the [[University of Southern Queensland]], and in 1999 he relocated to Melbourne to undertake his [[honours degree|Honours]] in Fine Art at the [[RMIT University|Royal Melbourne Institute of Technology]].<ref name=rmit>{{cite web | title=RMIT alumni receive Queen\u2019s Birthday honours | website=RMIT University | date=21 June 2018 | url=https://www.rmit.edu.au/news/all-news/2018/jun/rmit-alumni-receive-queens-birthday-honours | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhile studying at Toowoomba and Melbourne, Thompson was heavily inspired by [[Fluxus]] artists [[George Maciunas]] and [[Yoko Ono]], as well [[Andy Warhol]] and many others. He grew up immersed in music and culture of the 1980s and '90s and identified strongly with [[punk music]].<ref name=mckenzie>{{cite interview | interviewer-last=McKenzie | interviewer-first=Janet | title=Christian Thompson interview: \u2018My work does not need to be read through the optical lens of my race\u2019|first=Christian|last=Thompson | website=Studio International | url=https://www.studiointernational.com/index.php/christian-thompson-australian-indigenous-interview | access-date=15 April 2020|date=10 Nov 2014}}</ref>\n\nHe was an active member of the Melbourne art community, exhibiting his own work and curating group exhibitions. He undertook a curatorial internship at the [[Australian Centre for the Moving Image]], and was on the curatorial group for shows Contemporary Commonwealth at the [[National Gallery of Victoria]] and the Australian Centre for the Moving Image. He established the MHUL Workshop, an annual workshop for young Indigenous artists from across Australia.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 2009 he completed a Masters of Theatre degree at the DasArts, part of the [[Amsterdam School of the Arts]]. In 2010 he transferred to the [[Ruskin School of Art]]<ref name=academia>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson - University of Oxford | website=Academia.edu | date=3 August 2015 | url=https://oxford.academia.edu/ChristianThompson | language=af | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=mckenzie/> at the [[University of Oxford]], after being awarded the [[Charles Perkins (Aboriginal activist)|Charlie Perkins]] Scholarship, to complete his [[doctorate]] (Doctorate of Philosophy (Fine Art)<ref name=academia/>}. He was one of the first two [[Indigenous Australians]] to attend Oxford.<ref name=abc2018/>\n\nHe moved to [[London]] some time after his time at Oxford.<ref name=bbc2015/> He said in 2014 that \"a third of my life experiences and memories [were] attached to Europe\", after his time in [[the Netherlands]] and [[England]], and he had a worldview, which influenced his work. As his mother's family was from [[Bampton, Oxfordshire]],<ref name=bbc2015/> he also grew up surrounded by British television shows, and he looked to England rather than the [[United States]], as many young people of his age did.<ref name=mckenzie/>\n\n==Career==\nThompson meditated on the relationship between form and performance, and his early works focused on the relationship to the human form. He later moved into photography and [[video]] as a means to capture the performative qualities of his textile-based [[sculpture]]s and elaborate costumes.<ref name=agnsw>{{cite web | title=Christian Bumbarra Thompson  | website= [[Art Gallery of NSW]] | date=28 January 2015 | url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/resources/exhibition-kits/embodiment/christian-bumbarra-thompson/ | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThompson established himself in 2002 in the Australian art world with his first series, ''Blaks Palace'', a series of photographs and giant oversized sweaters. Thompson's most notable works include his series ''Emotional Striptease'', ''The Gates of Tambo'' and more recently his series ''Australian Graffiti'', which are held in the collections of the [[National Gallery of Australia]] and the [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]] and AAMU in [[Utrecht]], the Netherlands. His work deals with the nature of [[identity (social science)|identity]] as an ever-evolving and uncharted terrain, bringing together a variety of seemingly disparate forms and themes. He undertook his first major public art project through the Future Arts Research program at the [[Arizona State University]],<ref>{{cite web | title=F.A.R. (Future Arts Research) Launches at Arizona State University  | date=11 September 2008 | url=https://www.artandeducation.net/announcements/111257/f-a-r-future-arts-research-launches-at-arizona-state-university | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> [[Dartmouth College]], and [[Massey University]] International Art Residency, [[Wellington]], New Zealand.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nHis series of photographs ''Lost Together'' was made in the Netherlands where Thompson undertook a residency program at [[DasArts]] developing his live performance work which brought together his Bidjara and European heritage, combining classical music, traditional rhythms and lyrical narratives into richly textured, lilting and evocative arrangements. His sound based work is concerned with the innate lyricism of his traditional language and the expression of this in contemporary traditional and experimental musical forms. His work has appeared in various national and international publications including [[frieze (magazine)|''Frieze'']], ''Art and Australia'', ''Art Monthly'', ''Realtime'', ''Art Review'', ''Vogue'' magazine and in [[Susan Bright]]'s book ''Auto Focus'' published by [[Thames & Hudson]]. Thompson was also shortlisted and highly commended for the [[Kate Challis RAKA Award]] and in 2011 for the [[Blake Prize for Religious Art|Blake Prize]] and the [[Basil Sellers Art Prize]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Exhibitions and gallery holdings==\nHe has presented his photographs, videos and performance work in numerous solo and group exhibitions nationally and internationally. He was the first Aboriginal studio artist at Gertrude Street Contemporary Art Spaces 2006\u20132007,<ref name=westspace>{{cite web | title=Vote Yes - An Aboriginal Thompson Project: Christian Thompson: 26 May \u2013 10 Jun 2006| website=West Space | url=https://westspace.org.au/exhi/6398/view  | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> Melbourne. In 2008 he began international residencies at DasArts Advanced Studies for Performing Arts, [[Amsterdam]], and [[Arizona State University]] in the United States. His work is held in many public and private collections in Australia and overseas, including the [[National Gallery of Australia]], National Gallery of Victoria, [[Art Gallery of New South Wales]], [[Queensland Art Gallery]], the [[Kluge-Ruhe Aboriginal Art Collection]] of the [[University of Virginia]], the Peter Klein Collection ([[Eberdingen]], Germany), Latrobe Regional Gallery ([[Morwell, Victoria|Morwell, Australia]]), Aboriginal Art Museum ([[Utrecht]], the Netherlands), Myer Collection (Melbourne, Australia), City of Melbourne Collection, the [[Patrick Corrigan (businessman)#Australian art and photography|Pat Corrigan Collection]], [[Artbank]], [[Cate Blanchett]] and [[Andrew Upton]] collection and private collections.<ref>[https://www.christianthompson.net/cv Christian Thompson CV]</ref>\n\nHis work was included in the [[Biennale of Sydney#17th Biennale of Sydney (2010)|17th International Biennale of Sydney]] ''The Beauty of Distance - Songs of Survival in a Precarious Age'', curated by David Elliot,{{cn|date=April 2020}} and the 2018 [[Adelaide Biennial of Australian Art]] ''Before and After Science'',<ref>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson | website=2018 Adelaide Biennial of Australian Art | url=http://adelaidebiennial.com.au/2018/artist/christian-thompson/ | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> curated by Sarah Tutton and Charlotte Day. In 2010 he was shortlisted for the [[Art Gallery of Western Australia]] [[Western Australian Indigenous Art Awards|Indigenous Art Award]] along with artists such as [[Makinti Napanangka]], [[Gulumbu Yunupingu]], Judy Watson, Wakartu Cory Surprise and Richard Bell. In 2011 Thompson undertook international residencies at the [[Australia Council for the Arts]] Greene street Studio, New York and the Fonderie Darling Studio, Montreal. His work ''Gamu Mambu'' from the Sydney Biennale was included in a major exhibition of Korean and Australian art at the [[Museum of Contemporary Art Australia]].{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nThompson's video work ''HEAT 2010'' was included in the [[National Gallery of Australia]]'s 2nd [[National Indigenous Art Triennial]]: ''unDISCLOSED'' in 2012.<ref>{{cite web | title=unDISCLOSED: 2nd National Indigenous Art Triennial | website=National Gallery of Australia  | date=19 September 2010 | url=https://nga.gov.au/exhibition/undisclosed/default.cfm?MnuID=ARTISTS&GALID=6549&viewID=3 | access-date=15 April 2020}}</ref> In 2014 he became the first recipient of the [[Massey University]] international arts residency in New Zealand.<ref>{{cite web|title=New international arts residency has contemporary focus|url=http://creative.massey.ac.nz/about/news/2014/july/new-international-arts-residency-has-contemporary-focus/|website=[[Massey University]]|accessdate=23 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis 2011 video work ''Dhagunyilangu'', meaning brother, employs a British male opera singer to interpret the song written in [[Bidjara language|Bidjara]], one of many [[Aboriginal Australian languages|Aboriginal languages]] which have been lost during colonisation.<ref>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson - Dhagunyilangu | website=Michael Reid | date=27 July 2016 | url=https://michaelreid.com.au/communication/art-tube/christian-thompson-dhagunyilangu/ | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> It was  included in the [[TarraWarra Biennial]] in [[Melbourne]]<ref>{{cite web | title=in the loop sept 5: quick picks & opportunities: tarrawarra biennial 2012: sonic spheres | website=RealTime | date=4 September 2012 | url=https://www.realtime.org.au/in-the-loop-sept-5-quick-picks-opportunities/ | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> as well as the [[Pitt Rivers Museum]] at Oxford University in 2012, as part of the photographic series, ''We Bury Our Own''.<ref name=pitt>{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson: We Bury Our Own | website=Pitt Rivers Museum | date=26 June 2012 | url=https://www.prm.ox.ac.uk/event/christian-thompson-we-bury-our-own | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> He said in 2015 that the impact of this series on other artists and academics had been the most rewarding thing for him in his career to date.<ref name=bbc2015/>\n\nHe collaborated with [[James Young (British musician) |James Young]], former collaborator of [[Nico]], and recorded his own version of ''Dhagunyilangu'' and created a [[video]] work of himself singing in Bidjara as part of the [[Massey University]] International Art Residency, [[Wellington, New Zealand]]. The video work titled ''Refuge'' is part of a larger series of works titled ''Eight Limbs'' shown at the [[Te Whare Hera Gallery]], Wellington, in 2014.\n\nIn January 2015, Oxford's [[Trinity College, Oxford|Trinity College]] took down the old paintings in its [[dining room]] for the first time in over 400 years to display an exhibition of Thompson's work.<ref name=bbc2015>{{cite web | last=Sebag-Montefiore | first=Clarissa | title=Indigenous artist forges new path | website=BBC News | date=21 August 2015 | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-33955865 | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first survey of his work, an exhibition called ''Ritual Intimacy'', presented in association with [[Monash University Museum of Art]] (MUMA) and cureated by [[Hetti Perkins]] and [[Charlotte Day (curator)|Charlotte Day]], was mounted at [[UNSW Art & Design]] Galleries in Paddington from May to July 2018.<ref name=\"UNSW Art & Design 2018\">{{cite web | title=Christian Thompson: Ritual Intimacy | website=UNSW Art & Design | date=14 July 2018 | url=https://artdesign.unsw.edu.au/unsw-galleries/christian-thompson-ritual-intimacy | access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref> after being mounted at MUMA, [[Griffith University Art Museum]] in [[Brisbane]] and the [[Samstag Museum of Art]] in Adelaide.<ref name=abc2018/>\n\nFrom May 2018 he worked on his first [[virtual reality]] project,<ref name=abc2018/> under the [[Australian Centre for the Moving Image]] Mordant Family VR Commission. It was mounted at ACMI in May 2019, titled ''Bayi Gardiya (Singing Desert)''. In the seven-minute installation, Thompson sings in the [[Bidjara language]], which had been lost but is being revived. Thompson is the first recipient of the Mordant Family Commission VR, a three-year program worth {{AUD|240,000}} to support artists who have never worked in VR before.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.acmi.net.au/events/christian-thompson-bayi-gardiya-singing-desert/|title=Dr Christian Thompson AO: Bayi Gardiya (Singing Desert)|website=ACMI|access-date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n\nIn 2010, Thompson was awarded the inaugural [[Charles Perkins (Aboriginal activist)|Charlie Perkins]] Scholarship to the [[University of Oxford]] to undertake his Doctorate of Philosophy (Fine Art), and was among the first cohort of Australian Aboriginal people to attend Oxford University in its 900-year history.<ref name=rmit/><ref name=abc2018/>\n\nIn 2018, he was made an Officer in the General Division of the [[Order of Australia]] in the [[2018 Queen's Birthday Honours (Australia)]], for \"outstanding service to the visual arts as a sculptor, photographer, video and performance artist, and as a role model for young Indigenous artists\".<ref name=rmit/>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web | title=Andy and Oz: parallel visions: A collaboration between the National Gallery of Australia and The Andy Warhol Museum, Pittsburgh, USA.| website=National Gallery of Australia  | date=30 December 2007 | url=https://nga.gov.au/andyandoz/index.cfm}}\n*{{cite web | title=Christian Bumbarra Thompson  | website=Art Gallery of NSW | date=28 January 2015 | url=https://www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au/resources/exhibition-kits/embodiment/christian-bumbarra-thompson/ }}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|www.christianthompson.net}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thompson, Christian}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian Aboriginal artists]]\n[[Category:Australian contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Australian performance artists]]\n[[Category:Australian photographers]]\n[[Category:Bidjara]]\n[[Category:People from Gawler, South Australia]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Laterthanyouthink", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life, influences and education:add date", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Thompson_(artist)"}
{"title_page": "Padmapani Acharya", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Major]]\n| name          = Padmapani Acharya\n| honorific_suffix = [[Maha Vir Chakra|MVC]]\n| image         = Padmapani_Acharya_MVC.jpg\n| image_size    = 250 px\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1969|6|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Odisha]], [[India]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1999|6|28|1969|6|21|df=y}}\n| death_place   = Tololing, [[Kargil district|Kargil]], [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[India]]\n| nickname      = \n| rank          = [[File:Major of the Indian Army.svg|20px]] [[Major]]\n| allegiance    = {{flagicon|India}} [[Republic of India]]\n| branch        = {{army|India}}\n| unit          = [[Rajputana Rifles|2 Rajputana Rifles]]\n| serviceyears  = 1994-1999\n| battles       = '''[[Kargil War]]'''<br>[[Operation Vijay (1999)|Operation Vijay]]\n| awards        = [[File:Maha Vir Chakra ribbon.svg|32px]] [[Maha Vir Chakra]]\n}}\n\n[[Major]] '''Padmapani Acharya''', [[Maha Vir Chakra|MVC]] (21 June 1969&nbsp;\u2013 28 June 1999) was an officer in the [[Indian Army]]. He was awarded the second highest Indian military honour, [[Maha Vir Chakra]] posthumously for his actions during the [[Kargil War]] on 28 June 1999.<ref>[http://news.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/oct/14/slide-show-1-when-i-met-the-family-of-a-kargil-martyr.htm When I met the family of a Kargil martyr - Rediff.com News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.bellinfosys.com/soldier.htm India Kargil War Heros Sons of Brave parents Indian Army Soldiers<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaj. Acharya was originally from [[Odisha]] and was a resident of [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Telangana]]. Maj Acharya, was married to Charulatha. Acharya's father, Jagannath Acharya, was a retired [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] of the [[Indian Air Force]], during 1965 and 1971 [[Indo-Pakistani wars and conflicts|wars with Pakistan]]. He then worked with the [[Defence Research and Development Laboratory]] (DRDL) in Hyderabad.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/news/1999/jul/03kash5.htm Rediff On The NeT:The brave son of Andhra returns home<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Maj. Acharya was survived by his parents, wife and his daughter, Aparajita, who was born a few months after his death. Aparajita Acharya has been an [[National Cadet Corps (India)|NCC]] cadet.\n\n==Military Career==\nAcharya graduated from the [[Officers Training Academy]], [[Madras]] in 1983 and was commissioned as a [[Second Lieutenant]] into the 2nd battalion, [[Rajputana Rifles|The Rajputana Rifles]] (2 Raj Rif). \n\n===Kargil War===\nAt the outbreak of the [[Kargil War]], Acharya was in command of a [[Company (military unit)|Company]] of 2 Raj Rif. Acharya\u2019s previous conversations with his family, give an insight about his psyche and calm state of mind. About ten days before his march to the peak, he had written to his father, discussing personal as well as military issues. In a heart-numbing, straightforward letter, he said,\n\n''\u201cDear Papa\u2026 don\u2019t worry about casualties- it\u2019s a professional hazard beyond our control. At least it is for a good cause. Tell mamma that combat is an honour of a lifetime and I could not think of anything less. What better way to serve the nation? Tell a story a day from the Mahabharata to Charu so that your grandchild imbibes good values.\u201d''\n\n===Maha Vir Chakra===\nThe citation for the [[Maha Vir Chakra]] reads as follows:<ref>{{cite web |title=PADMAPANI ACHARYA {{!}} Gallantry Awards |url=https://gallantryawards.gov.in/Awardee/padmapani-acharya |website=gallantryawards.gov.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mahavir Chakra (MVC), Awardee: Maj Padmapani Acharya, MVC @ TWDI |url=http://twdi.in/node/1301 |website=twdi.in}}</ref>\n{{Quotation|Gazette Notification: 17 Pres/2000,15.8.99\nOperation: Op Vijay - Kargil\nDate of Award: 15 Aug 1999\n\n<center>'''CITATION'''<br>\n'''MAJOR PADMAPANI ACHARYA (IC-55072)'''<br>\n'''2 RAJPUTANA RIFLES'''<br/>\n'''(POSTHUMOUS)'''</center>\n\nOn 28 June 1999, Major Padmapani Acharya as a Company Commander, was assigned the formidable task of capturing an enemy position which was heavily fortified, strongly held and covered with mines and sweeping machine gun and artillery fire. Success of the battalion and brigade operation hinged on the early capture of this position. However the company attack almost faltered at the very beginning when the enemy's artillery fire came down squarely on the leading platoon, inflicting large numbers of casualties. With utter disregard to his personal safely, Major Acharya took the reserve platoon of his company and led it through raining artillery shells. Even as his men were falling to the murderous enemy fire, he continued to encourage his men and charged at the enemy up the steep rock face with his reserve platoon.\n\nUnmindful of the hail of bullets from the enemy's position, Major Acharya crawled up to the enemy position and lobbed grenades. In this daring assault, he was seriously injured. Despite heavy injuries and unable to move, he ordered his men to leave him and charge at the enemy while he continued to fire at the enemy. The enemy position was finally over-run and the objective was captured. He, however, succumbed to his injuries after completion of the mission.|sign=|source=}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe events of [[Battle of Tololing]] was adapted as one of the prominent battle scenes in the [[Hindi]], [[war film]] ''[[LOC Kargil]]'' in which actor [[Nagarjuna Akkineni]] portrayed the role of Acharya.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/fourteen-years-on-memories-still-fresh-in-majors-family/article4949781.ece Fourteen years on, memories still fresh in Major's family - The Hindu<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Neikezhakuo Kenguruse]]\n* [[Digendra Kumar]]\n* [[Magod Basappa Ravindranath]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Acharya, Padmapani}}\n[[Category:Indian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Maha Vir Chakra]]\n[[Category:People of the Kargil War]]\n[[Category:People from Odisha]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Major]]\n| name          = Padmapani Acharya\n| honorific_suffix = [[Maha Vir Chakra|MVC]]\n| image         = Padmapani_Acharya_MVC.jpg\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1969|6|21|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Odisha]], [[India]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1999|6|28|1969|6|21|df=y}}\n| death_place   = Tololing, [[Kargil district|Kargil]], [[Jammu and Kashmir]], [[India]]\n| nickname      = \n| rank          = [[File:Major of the Indian Army.svg|20px]] [[Major]]\n| allegiance    = {{flagicon|India}} [[Republic of India]]\n| branch        = {{army|India}}\n| unit          = [[Rajputana Rifles|2 Rajputana Rifles]]\n| serviceyears  = 1994-1999\n| battles       = '''[[Kargil War]]'''<br>[[Operation Vijay (1999)|Operation Vijay]]\n| awards        = [[File:Maha Vir Chakra ribbon.svg|32px]] [[Maha Vir Chakra]]\n}}\n\n[[Major]] '''Padmapani Acharya''', [[Maha Vir Chakra|MVC]] (21 June 1969&nbsp;\u2013 28 June 1999) was an officer in the [[Indian Army]]. He was awarded the second highest Indian military honour, [[Maha Vir Chakra]] posthumously for his actions during the [[Kargil War]] on 28 June 1999.<ref>[http://news.rediff.com/slide-show/2010/oct/14/slide-show-1-when-i-met-the-family-of-a-kargil-martyr.htm When I met the family of a Kargil martyr - Rediff.com News<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[http://www.bellinfosys.com/soldier.htm India Kargil War Heros Sons of Brave parents Indian Army Soldiers<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMaj. Acharya was originally from [[Odisha]] and was a resident of [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]], [[Telangana]]. Maj Acharya, was married to Charulatha. Acharya's father, Jagannath Acharya, was a retired [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] of the [[Indian Air Force]], during 1965 and 1971 [[Indo-Pakistani wars and conflicts|wars with Pakistan]]. He then worked with the [[Defence Research and Development Laboratory]] (DRDL) in Hyderabad.<ref>[http://www.rediff.com/news/1999/jul/03kash5.htm Rediff On The NeT:The brave son of Andhra returns home<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Maj. Acharya was survived by his parents, wife and his daughter, Aparajita, who was born a few months after his death. Aparajita Acharya has been an [[National Cadet Corps (India)|NCC]] cadet.\n\n==Military Career==\nAcharya graduated from the [[Officers Training Academy]], [[Madras]] in 1983 and was commissioned as a [[Second Lieutenant]] into the 2nd battalion, [[Rajputana Rifles|The Rajputana Rifles]] (2 Raj Rif). \n\n===Kargil War===\nAt the outbreak of the [[Kargil War]], Acharya was in command of a [[Company (military unit)|Company]] of 2 Raj Rif. Acharya\u2019s previous conversations with his family, give an insight about his psyche and calm state of mind. About ten days before his march to the peak, he had written to his father, discussing personal as well as military issues. In a heart-numbing, straightforward letter, he said,\n\n''\u201cDear Papa\u2026 don\u2019t worry about casualties- it\u2019s a professional hazard beyond our control. At least it is for a good cause. Tell mamma that combat is an honour of a lifetime and I could not think of anything less. What better way to serve the nation? Tell a story a day from the Mahabharata to Charu so that your grandchild imbibes good values.\u201d''\n\n===Maha Vir Chakra===\nThe citation for the [[Maha Vir Chakra]] reads as follows:<ref>{{cite web |title=PADMAPANI ACHARYA {{!}} Gallantry Awards |url=https://gallantryawards.gov.in/Awardee/padmapani-acharya |website=gallantryawards.gov.in}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Mahavir Chakra (MVC), Awardee: Maj Padmapani Acharya, MVC @ TWDI |url=http://twdi.in/node/1301 |website=twdi.in}}</ref>\n{{Quotation|Gazette Notification: 17 Pres/2000,15.8.99\nOperation: Op Vijay - Kargil\nDate of Award: 15 Aug 1999\n\n<center>'''CITATION'''<br>\n'''MAJOR PADMAPANI ACHARYA (IC-55072)'''<br>\n'''2 RAJPUTANA RIFLES'''<br/>\n'''(POSTHUMOUS)'''</center>\n\nOn 28 June 1999, Major Padmapani Acharya as a Company Commander, was assigned the formidable task of capturing an enemy position which was heavily fortified, strongly held and covered with mines and sweeping machine gun and artillery fire. Success of the battalion and brigade operation hinged on the early capture of this position. However the company attack almost faltered at the very beginning when the enemy's artillery fire came down squarely on the leading platoon, inflicting large numbers of casualties. With utter disregard to his personal safely, Major Acharya took the reserve platoon of his company and led it through raining artillery shells. Even as his men were falling to the murderous enemy fire, he continued to encourage his men and charged at the enemy up the steep rock face with his reserve platoon.\n\nUnmindful of the hail of bullets from the enemy's position, Major Acharya crawled up to the enemy position and lobbed grenades. In this daring assault, he was seriously injured. Despite heavy injuries and unable to move, he ordered his men to leave him and charge at the enemy while he continued to fire at the enemy. The enemy position was finally over-run and the objective was captured. He, however, succumbed to his injuries after completion of the mission.|sign=|source=}}\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe events of [[Battle of Tololing]] was adapted as one of the prominent battle scenes in the [[Hindi]], [[war film]] ''[[LOC Kargil]]'' in which actor [[Nagarjuna Akkineni]] portrayed the role of Acharya.<ref>[http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Hyderabad/fourteen-years-on-memories-still-fresh-in-majors-family/article4949781.ece Fourteen years on, memories still fresh in Major's family - The Hindu<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Neikezhakuo Kenguruse]]\n* [[Digendra Kumar]]\n* [[Magod Basappa Ravindranath]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Acharya, Padmapani}}\n[[Category:Indian Army officers]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Maha Vir Chakra]]\n[[Category:People of the Kargil War]]\n[[Category:People from Odisha]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n", "name_user": "Koushik Pain", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Padmapani_Acharya"}
{"title_page": "Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Central Eastside\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = Subdistrict\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_size              = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = USA Oregon Portland\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|45.515097|-122.660782|region:US-OR_type:city|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = [http://www.portlandonline.com/shared/cfm/image.cfm?id=58593 PDF map]\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1       = State\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Oregon]]\n| subdivision_type2       = City\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            = \n| leader_title2           = \n| leader_name2            = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = US\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| area_footnotes          = <ref>{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/portfolio-items/central-eastside/ |title=Central Eastside |publisher=[[Prosper Portland]] |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415180942/https://prosperportland.us/portfolio-items/central-eastside/ |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_total_sq_mi        = 1.11\n| dimensions_footnotes    = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_ft            = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| demographics_type1      = \n| demographics1_footnotes = \n| demographics1_title1    = No. of households\n| demographics1_info1     = \n| demographics1_title2    = Occupancy rate\n| demographics1_info2     = \n| demographics1_title3    = {{nowrap|Owner-occupied}}\n| demographics1_info3     = \n| demographics1_title4    = Renting\n| demographics1_info4     = \n| demographics1_title5    = Avg. household size\n| demographics1_info5     = \n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Central Eastside''' is a [[subdistrict]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States. It is situated in [[Neighborhoods of Portland, Oregon#Southeast|Southeast Portland]] along the east bank of the [[Willamette River]] and makes up a part of Portland's Central City district.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|East Portland, Oregon}}\n\nIn 1845, [[Oregon Trail]] pioneer [[James B. Stephens]] laid claim to {{convert|640|acre|ha}} of land situated directly across the [[Willamette River]] from the then-newly established [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] townsite.<ref name=\"east-portland-1874\">{{cite web |url=https://oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/east-portland-1874/ |title=East Portland, 1874 |publisher=[[Oregon Historical Society]] |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The land had been controlled by [[John McLoughlin]] of the [[Hudson\u2019s Bay Company]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.opb.org/artsandlife/series/historical-photo/oregon-historical-photo-city-of-east-portland/ |last=Rosman |first=John |title=Oregon Historical Photo: The City Of East Portland |date=May 12, 2014 |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"forgotten-city\">{{cite web |url=http://visitahc.org/wp-content/uploads/Exhibit-booklet.pdf |title=East Portland: A Changing Landscape, A Forgotten City |publisher=Architectural Heritage Center |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415215652/http://visitahc.org/wp-content/uploads/Exhibit-booklet.pdf |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2}} The area consisted of [[orchard]]s and [[hay]], and its location along the east bank of the river\u2014with its [[marsh]]es, [[creek]]s, and [[Slough (hydrology)|slough]]s\u2014made development challenging.<ref name=\"guo-2014\">{{cite report |url=https://www.pdx.edu/sba/sites/www.pdx.edu.sba/files/01%20Central%20Eastside%20-%20Guo.pdf |last=Guo |first=Angela |title=The Evolution of Portland's Central Eastside |work=Center for Real Estate Quarterly Report |volume=8 |number=2 |publisher=[[Portland State University]] |date=2014 |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|3}} Stephens established the Stark Street Ferry to link the east and west sides of the river in 1848. A mule on a treadmill powered the vessel's [[paddle wheel]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Terry |first=John |title=Hundreds of ferries once served Oregonians; now there are just three |date=Oct 15, 2011 |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/O/2011/10/hundreds_of_ferries_once_serve.html |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> On April{{nbsp}}16, 1868, the [[Oregon Central Railroad]] broke ground at the settlement, which by then was being referred to as [[East Portland, Oregon|East Portland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/12264 |title=1868 Invitation to railroad groundbreaking |publisher=City of Portland Archives and Records Management |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415213419/https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/12264 |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> A rail line extended from [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]] the following year, helping to start the development of an industrial economy based on the shipment of agricultural products across the [[Willamette Valley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://beta.portland.gov/sites/default/files/2020-01/portlands-central-eastside-2013.pdf |title=Portland Central Eastside |publisher=City of Portland Bureau of Planning and Sustainability |date=January 2020 |page=2 |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415190953/https://beta.portland.gov/sites/default/files/2020-01/portlands-central-eastside-2013.pdf |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The railroad's presence led Stephens to incorporate the City of East Portland in 1870 with its population of 8,293.<ref name=\"forgotten-city\"/>{{rp|6}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/284518 |title=Portland Historical Timeline: 1843 to 1901 |publisher=City of Portland Archives and Records Management |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://ceic.cc/ Central Eastside Industrial Council]\n\n{{Portland neighborhoods}}\n\n[[Category:Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon| ]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Southeast Portland, Oregon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Central Eastside\n| native_name             = \n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = Subdistrict\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_size              = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| image_flag              = \n| flag_alt                = \n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = \n| shield_alt              = \n| nickname                = \n| motto                   = \n| image_map               = \n| map_alt                 = \n| map_caption             = \n| pushpin_map             = USA Oregon Portland\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = \n| coordinates             = {{coord|45.515097|-122.660782|region:US-OR_type:city|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_footnotes   = [http://www.portlandonline.com/shared/cfm/image.cfm?id=58593 PDF map]\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[United States]]\n| subdivision_type1       = State\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Oregon]]\n| subdivision_type2       = City\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]\n| established_title       = \n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| seat_type               = \n| seat                    = \n| leader_title1           = \n| leader_name1            = \n| leader_title2           = \n| leader_name2            = \n| government_footnotes    = \n| leader_party            = \n| leader_title            = \n| leader_name             = \n| unit_pref               = US\n<!-- ALL fields with measurements have automatic unit conversion -->\n<!-- for references: use <ref> tags -->\n| area_footnotes          = <ref>{{cite web |url=https://prosperportland.us/portfolio-items/central-eastside/ |title=Central Eastside |publisher=[[Prosper Portland]] |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200415180942/https://prosperportland.us/portfolio-items/central-eastside/ |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2          = \n| area_total_sq_mi        = 1.11\n| dimensions_footnotes    = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_ft            = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_density_sq_mi = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_note         = \n| demographics_type1      = \n| demographics1_footnotes = \n| demographics1_title1    = No. of households\n| demographics1_info1     = \n| demographics1_title2    = Occupancy rate\n| demographics1_info2     = \n| demographics1_title3    = {{nowrap|Owner-occupied}}\n| demographics1_info3     = \n| demographics1_title4    = Renting\n| demographics1_info4     = \n| demographics1_title5    = Avg. household size\n| demographics1_info5     = \n| timezone1               = \n| utc_offset1             = \n| timezone1_DST           = \n| utc_offset1_DST         = \n| postal_code_type        = \n| postal_code             = \n| area_code_type          = \n| area_code               = \n| iso_code                = \n| website                 = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Central Eastside''' is a [[subdistrict]] in [[Portland, Oregon]], United States. It is situated in [[Neighborhoods of Portland, Oregon#Southeast|Southeast Portland]] along the east bank of the [[Willamette River]] and makes up a part of Portland's Central City district.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|East Portland, Oregon}}\n\nIn 1845, [[Oregon Trail]] pioneer [[James B. Stephens]] laid claim to {{convert|640|acre|ha}} of land situated directly across the [[Willamette River]] from the then-newly established [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] townsite.<ref name=\"east-portland-1874\">{{cite web |url=https://oregonhistoryproject.org/articles/historical-records/east-portland-1874/ |title=East Portland, 1874 |publisher=[[Oregon Historical Society]] |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The land had been controlled by [[John McLoughlin]] of the [[Hudson\u2019s Bay Company]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.opb.org/artsandlife/series/historical-photo/oregon-historical-photo-city-of-east-portland/ |last=Rosman |first=John |title=Oregon Historical Photo: The City Of East Portland |date=May 12, 2014 |publisher=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"forgotten-city\">{{cite web |url=http://visitahc.org/wp-content/uploads/Exhibit-booklet.pdf |title=East Portland: A Changing Landscape, A Forgotten City |publisher=Architectural Heritage Center |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415215652/http://visitahc.org/wp-content/uploads/Exhibit-booklet.pdf |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|2}} The area consisted of [[orchard]]s and [[hay]], and its location along the east bank of the river\u2014with its [[marsh]]es, [[creek]]s, and [[Slough (hydrology)|slough]]s\u2014made development challenging.<ref name=\"guo-2014\">{{cite report |url=https://www.pdx.edu/sba/sites/www.pdx.edu.sba/files/01%20Central%20Eastside%20-%20Guo.pdf |last=Guo |first=Angela |title=The Evolution of Portland's Central Eastside |work=Center for Real Estate Quarterly Report |volume=8 |number=2 |publisher=[[Portland State University]] |date=2014 |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>{{rp|3}} Stephens established the Stark Street Ferry to link the east and west sides of the river in 1848. A mule on a treadmill powered the vessel's [[paddle wheel]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Terry |first=John |title=Hundreds of ferries once served Oregonians; now there are just three |date=Oct 15, 2011 |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |url=https://www.oregonlive.com/O/2011/10/hundreds_of_ferries_once_serve.html |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> On April{{nbsp}}16, 1868, the [[Oregon Central Railroad]] broke ground at the settlement, which by then was being referred to as [[East Portland, Oregon|East Portland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/12264 |title=1868 Invitation to railroad groundbreaking |publisher=City of Portland Archives and Records Management |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415213419/https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/12264 |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The line extended from [[Salem, Oregon|Salem]] in the following year, helping to start the development of an industrial economy based on the shipment of agricultural products across the [[Willamette Valley]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://beta.portland.gov/sites/default/files/2020-01/portlands-central-eastside-2013.pdf |title=Portland Central Eastside |publisher=City of Portland Bureau of Planning and Sustainability |date=January 2020 |page=2 |access-date=April 15, 2020 |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200415190953/https://beta.portland.gov/sites/default/files/2020-01/portlands-central-eastside-2013.pdf |archive-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref> The railroad's presence led Stephens to incorporate the City of East Portland in 1870 with its population of 8,293.<ref name=\"forgotten-city\"/>{{rp|6}}<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/archives/article/284518 |title=Portland Historical Timeline: 1843 to 1901 |publisher=City of Portland Archives and Records Management |access-date=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://ceic.cc/ Central Eastside Industrial Council]\n\n{{Portland neighborhoods}}\n\n[[Category:Central Eastside, Portland, Oregon| ]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Southeast Portland, Oregon]]\n", "name_user": "Truflip99", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Central_Eastside,_Portland,_Oregon"}
{"title_page": "Tate Reeves", "text_new": "{{short description|65th Governor of Mississippi}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{original research|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Tate Reeves\n|image        = Tate Reeves 2019.jpg\n|order        = 65th [[List of governors of Mississippi|Governor of Mississippi]]\n|lieutenant   = [[Delbert Hosemann]] \n|term_start   = January 14, 2020\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Phil Bryant]]\n|successor    = \n|office2      = 32nd [[Lieutenant Governor of Mississippi]]\n|governor2    = Phil Bryant\n|term_start2  = January 10, 2012\n|term_end2    = January 14, 2020\n|predecessor2 = Phil Bryant\n|successor2   = Delbert Hosemann\n|office3      = 53rd [[Mississippi State Treasurer|Treasurer of Mississippi]]\n|governor3    = [[Haley Barbour]]\n|term_start3  = January 13, 2004\n|term_end3    = January 10, 2012\n|predecessor3 = Peyton Prospere\n|successor3   = [[Lynn Fitch]]\n|birth_name   = Jonathon Tate Reeves\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1974|6|5}}\n|birth_place  = [[Florence, Mississippi]], [[U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Elee Williams|November 24, 2001}}<ref>https://twitter.com/tatereeves/status/1198712273386250242</ref>\n|children     = 3\n|residence    = [[Mississippi Governor's Mansion|Governor's Mansion]]\n|education    = [[Millsaps College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n|website      = {{url|https://www.ms.gov/node/73|Government website}}\n}}\n\n'''Jonathon Tate Reeves''' (born June 5, 1974) is an [[United States|American]] politician who is the [[List of governors of Mississippi|65th]] [[governor of Mississippi]], serving since 2020, and was [[lieutenant governor of Mississippi]] from 2012 to 2020. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he was previously [[Mississippi State Treasurer]].<ref name=\"MISSISSIPPI FREE PRESS 2020\">{{cite web | title=Mississippi Churches, Stores Reopen As Governor Overrides Mayors\u2019 COVID-19 Orders | website=MISSISSIPPI FREE PRESS | date=2020-03-26 | url=https://www.mississippifreepress.com/mississippi-governor-overrides-mayors-covid-19.html | access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> At age 29, he was the youngest state treasurer in the nation when elected in 2003 and the first Republican to ever hold the office in Mississippi.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.treasury.state.ms.us/Biography/|title=Mississippi Treasurer Tate Reeves|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111083738/http://www.treasury.state.ms.us/Biography/|archivedate=January 11, 2012|url-status=dead|accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref> He was the Republican nominee for [[governor of Mississippi]] in the [[2019 Mississippi gubernatorial election|2019 election]]<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=As expected, GOP\u2019s Reeves files for Mississippi governor|url=http://msbusiness.com/2019/01/as-expected-gops-reeves-files-for-mississippi-governor/|work=[[Mississippi Business Journal]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 3, 2019|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=RunoffResults>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Jasmine C.|last2=Andre|first2=Mike|last3=White|first3=Isaac|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/08/27/us/elections/results-mississippi-primary-runoff-election.html|title=Mississippi Primary Runoff Election Results|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 27, 2019|accessdate=August 27, 2019}}</ref> and defeated Democratic Attorney General [[Jim Hood]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/politics/2019/11/05/tate-reeves-wins-mississippi-governor-race-defeats-jim-hood/4159647002/ |title=Republican Tate Reeves wins Mississippi governor race |first1=Luke|last1=Ramseth|first2=Giacomo|last2=Balogna|date=2019-11-05 |work=Mississippi Clarion Ledger |access-date=2019-11-06 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nA native of [[Rankin County, Mississippi|Rankin County]], Mississippi, Reeves graduated in 1992 from [[Florence High School (Mississippi)|Florence High School]] in [[Florence, Mississippi|Florence]]. He is an honors graduate of [[Millsaps College]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]], where he earned a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[economics]]. He played one year as a point guard for the Millsaps Majors [[basketball]] team and was a member of [[Kappa Alpha Order]]. Reeves remains involved with Millsaps by serving as a member of the investment policy board for the General Louis Wilson Fund and a member the Advisory Committee of the Else School of Management.\n\n==Early career==\nAfter Millsaps, Reeves pursued a career in banking and finance in Jackson, where he became assistant vice president for [[AmSouth]], formerly the Deposit Guaranty National Bank, and served as a senior investment analyst.<ref name=\"autogenerated5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tatereeves.com/biography.html |title=Biography of Tate Reeves|website=tatereeves.com|accessdate=July 4, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050816142757/http://www.tatereeves.com/biography.html |archivedate=August 16, 2005 }}</ref>  In 2000, Reeves became an investment officer for Trustmark National Bank in Jackson.\n\nReeves holds the [[Chartered Financial Analyst]] designation and is a member of the CFA Society of Mississippi and the [[CFA Institute]], an investment industry organization. In 1996, he was the recipient of the Mississippi Society of Financial Analysts Award.\n\n==Mississippi state treasurer==\n===Elections===\n====2003 state treasurer campaign====\nReeves entered the 2003 GOP [[primary election]] and faced former transportation commissioner Wayne Burkes of [[Brandon, Mississippi|Brandon]] and [[Mississippi House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Andrew Ketchings]] of [[Natchez, Mississippi|Natchez]]. Reeves ran strongly in GOP strongholds, including [[Lamar County, Mississippi|Lamar]], [[DeSoto County, Mississippi|DeSoto]], and Rankin counties.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}. In the three-candidate primary, Reeves led with 49% of the vote,<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/BX/lib00105,0FCC31C84D7566BF.html|title=\"Anderson, Reeves out to early leads in treasurer primaries\", The Sun Herald|accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref> and routed Burkes in the primary runoff.<ref name=\"autogenerated6\">{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BX&s_site=sunherald&p_multi=BX&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FD3BC479270A6A2&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=State and County races|work=[[The Sun-Herald|The Sun Herald]]|accessdate=July 4, 2011 | date=August 27, 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Reeves defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Nomination|nominee]] Gary Anderson, the state director of finance and administration, 52% to 48%.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rMROAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rg4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6719,3447079&dq=tate+reeves+wins+gary+anderson&hl=en|title=Race may have been factor in Miss. elections|last=Byrd|first=Sheila Hardwell|work=[[The Ocala Star-Banner]] |accessdate=July 4, 2011 | date=November 6, 2003}}</ref>\n\n====2007 treasurer election====\nUnopposed in the GOP primary, Reeves's only Democratic opposition in the 2007 general election was perennial candidate [[Shawn O'Hara]]. Reeves was reelected with 61% of the vote.\n\n===Tenure===\nAs treasurer, Reeves served as president of the National Association of State Treasurers in 2006\u201307. He is a member and former chairman of the Long Range Planning Committee and a member of the Federal Legislative Committee. He was previously a member of the NAST Executive Committee. Reeves represents the State of Mississippi as a member of the Executive Board of the College Savings Plans Network. He serves on the board of trustees for the Public Employees' Retirement System of Mississippi, and is the chairman of the board of directors of College Savings Plans of Mississippi and the Mississippi Health Care Trust Fund.\n\nIn 2007, ''Rising Tide'' magazine, the publication of the [[Republican National Committee]], named Reeves one of 42 national \"Rising Star(s) in the Republican Party\". In 2008, Reeves was elected president of the Mississippi Republican Elected Officials Association. In December 2008, the Aspen Institute's Rodel Fellowships in Public Leadership selected him as one of their \"Top Young Elected Officials\" in its Fourth Class of Aspen-Rodel Fellows. Reeves was recognized by his NAST peers as the recipient of the Jesse M. Unruh Award for his service to the association, the profession, and his state.\n\n==Lieutenant governor of Mississippi==\n===Elections===\n====2011 lieutenant governor campaign====\n\nIn February 2011, Reeves officially launched a campaign for lieutenant governor<ref name=\"autogenerated8\">{{cite news|url=http://www.clarionledger.com/article/20110208/NEWS/102080325/Reeves-launches-campaign-lt-gov-|title=Reeves launches campaign for lt.gov|last=Parker|first=Molly|work=[[The Clarion-Ledger]]|accessdate=July 4, 2011|date=February 6, 2011}}</ref> and held a fundraising lead over his primary opponent, [[Mississippi State Senate]]  [[President pro tempore|President Pro Tempore]] [[William Gardner Hewes|Billy Hewes]] of [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} A May 2011 poll of likely Republican voters showed Reeves with a 51%\u201318% lead over Hewes.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/56772731/Tate-Reeves-Billy-Hewes-Poll-052711|title=Memo re Mississippi Statewide Republican Primary Survey|date=May 26, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref>\nOn August 2, 2011, Reeves defeated Hewes. On November 8, he was elected lieutenant governor, succeeding [[Phil Bryant]], who was elected to his first term as [[governor of Mississippi|governor]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Reeves Wins Race For Miss. Lt. Governor |first= |last= |url=http://www.wapt.com/politics/29718333/detail.html |newspaper=[[WAPT (TV)|WAPT]] |date=November 8, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n====2015 reelection====\n\nReeves won reelection as lieutenant governor on November 3, 2015, defeating three opponents, including state Senator [[Timothy L. Johnson]], a Republican-turned-Democrat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wlox.com/story/30428879/tate-reeves-reelected-as-mississippi-governor|title=Tate Reeves re-elected as Mississippi Lt. Governor|date=November 3, 2015|publisher=[[WLOX]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref> Newspaper reporting on the misuse of statewide public official's campaign funds indicated that Reeves did not misuse these funds. Non-election year expenses were directed toward campaign-related items such as computer databases or political travel.<ref>Mollie Bryant, Geoffrey Sender, & Kate Royals. (March 6, 2016). \"Funds used to buy vehicles, pottery\". ''Clarion Ledger''. (Jackson). p. A15</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nReeves served as lieutenant governor from 2012 to 2020.\n\n==Governor of Mississippi==\n===Elections===\n====2019 campaign for governor====\nReeves ran for [[governor of Mississippi]] in the [[2019 Mississippi gubernatorial election|2019 election]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He opposed Medicaid expansion, which he called \u201cObamacare expansion.\u201d He lives in Flowood.\n\nIn the Republican primary, he and [[Bill Waller Jr.]] finished in first and second place, respectively. Because no candidate won a majority of the total vote, Reeves and Waller proceeded to a [[runoff election]] on August 27, which Reeves won.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/07/election-results-mississippi-governor-race-heading-runoff/1899155001/ |title=Tate Reeves, Bill Waller head to runoff for Republican governor primary |last=Bologna |first=Giacomo |date=2019-08-07 |work=Jackson Clarion-Ledger |access-date=2019-08-07 |last2=Ramseth |first2=Luke |language=en}}</ref><ref name=RunoffResults/>\n\n===Tenure===\nReeves was sworn in as governor on January 14, 2020. <ref>https://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2020/mar/24/gov-tate-reeves-orders-limited-gatherings-today-ex/</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\n\nIn the midst of the acceleration of the [[Covid-19]] [[pandemic]], Reeves overrode local leaders' decisions to order people to stay at home, instead telling Mississippians get back to \"life as usual\" and deeming places like bars, dine-in restaurants and churches \"essential services\". The decision was widely condemned.<ref>Adam Ganusheau [https://www.sunherald.com/news/politics-government/article241524861.html Mayors scramble to know: Does Gov. Reeves\u2019 coronavirus declaration clash with local orders?] March 26, 2020 ''[[Mississippi Today]]'' via ''[[Sun Herald]]''</ref> Reeves\u2019s Shelter in Place Order 1466 went into effect at 5pm on April 3.[https://www.sos.ms.gov/Education-Publications/ExecutiveOrders/1466.pdf order 1466]\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Treasurer Republican Primary Election, 2003\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves'''\n|80,770\n|48.48\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Wayne Burkes'''\n|51,745\n|31.06\n|-\n|Republican\n|Andrew Ketchings\n|33,795\n|20.28\n|-\n|Republican\n|Write-ins\n|311\n|0.19\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Treasurer Republican Primary Election Runoff, 2003\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves'''\n|49,466\n|72.16\n|-\n|Republican\n|Wayne Burkes\n|19,047\n|27.78\n|-\n|Republican\n|Write-ins\n|39\n|0.06\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Treasurer Election, 2003\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves'''\n|447,860\n|51.80\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Gary Anderson\n|403,307\n|46.64\n|-\n|Reform\n|Lee Dilworth\n|13,507\n|1.56\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Treasurer Election, 2007\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves (inc.)'''\n|436,833\n|60.53\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Shawn O'Hara\n|284,789\n|39.47\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Lieutenant Governor Republican Primary Election, 2011\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves'''\n|162,857\n|56.89\n|-\n|Republican\n|Billy Hewes\n|123,389\n|43.11\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Lieutenant Governor Election, 2011\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves'''\n|644,205\n|80.35\n|-\n|Reform\n|Tracella Lou O'Hara\n|157,547\n|19.65\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Lieutenant Governor Republican Primary Election, 2015\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves (inc.)'''\n|225,192\n|82.50\n|-\n|Republican\n|Alisha Nelson McElhenney\n|47,760\n|17.50\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Lieutenant Governor Election, 2015\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves (inc.)'''\n|429,990\n|60.45\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Tim Johnson\n|255,657\n|35.94\n|-\n|Libertarian\n|Ron Williams\n|16,226\n|2.28\n|-\n|Reform\n|Rosa Williams\n|9,410\n|1.32\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Governor Republican Primary Election, 2019\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves'''\n|182,979\n|48.9\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Bill Waller Jr.'''\n|124,707\n|33.3\n|-\n|Republican\n|Robert Foster\n|66,441\n|17.8\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Governor Republican Primary Election Runoff, 2019\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves'''\n|176,251\n|54.28\n|-\n|Republican\n|Bill Waller Jr.\n|148,471\n|45.72\n|}\n\n{{Election box begin|\n| title = Mississippi gubernatorial election, 2019<ref>{{cite web|url=https://data.clarionledger.com/mississippi-general-election-results-2019/ |title=Mississippi General Election Results 2019 |publisher=ClarionLedger.com |date=2019-11-05 |accessdate=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link \n| candidate = [[Tate Reeves]]\n| party = Republican Party (United States)\n| votes = 443,063\n| percentage = 52.26\n| change = -14.12%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| candidate = [[Jim Hood]]\n| party = Democratic Party (United States)\n| votes = 394,177\n| percentage = 46.49\n| change = +14.24%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n| candidate = David Singletary\n| party = Independent (United States)\n| votes = 8,145\n| percentage = 0.96\n| change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link \n| candidate = Bob Hickingbottom\n| party = Constitution Party (United States)\n| votes = 2,495\n| percentage = 0.29\n| change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box total no change\n| votes = 847,880\n| percentage = 100%\n| change = N/A\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link no swing\n  |winner     = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n* [https://www.tatereeves.com/ Official website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=Peyton Prospere}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mississippi State Treasurer|Treasurer of Mississippi]]|years=2004\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lynn Fitch]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Phil Bryant]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[List of lieutenant governors of Mississippi|Lieutenant Governor of Mississippi]]}}|years=2012\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Delbert Hosemann]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Mississippi|Governor of Mississippi]]|years=2020\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=Phil Bryant}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Mississippi|Governor of Mississippi]]|years=[[2019 Mississippi gubernatorial election|2019]]}}\n{{s-inc|recent}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before={{Incumbent VPOTUS}}|as=[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]]}}\n{{s-ttl|rows=2|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Within Mississippi}}\n{{s-aft|after=Mayor of city<br/>in which event is held}}\n|-\n{{s-aft|after=Otherwise {{Incumbent U.S. House Speaker}}<br/>{{nowrap|''{{small|as [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives]]}}''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Eric Holcomb]]|as=[[Governor of Indiana]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[United States order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the United States]]|years=Outside Mississippi}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[J. B. Pritzker]]|as=[[Governor of Illinois]]}} \n{{s-end}}\n\n{{U.S. governors}} \n{{Mississippi statewide political officials}}\n{{Governors of Mississippi}}\n{{Lieutenant Governors of Mississippi}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Mississippi|Sports|Politics|Business and Economics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reeves, Tate}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Mississippi]]\n[[Category:CFA charterholders]]\n[[Category:Governors of Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Lieutenant Governors of Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Millsaps College alumni]]\n[[Category:Mississippi Republicans]]\n[[Category:People from Florence, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:People from Flowood, Mississippi]]\n[[Category:Republican Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Mississippi]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|65th Governor of Mississippi}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{original research|date=February 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Tate Reeves\n|image        = Tate Reeves 2019.jpg\n|order        = 65th [[List of governors of Mississippi|Governor of Mississippi]]\n|lieutenant   = [[Delbert Hosemann]] \n|term_start   = January 14, 2020\n|term_end     = \n|predecessor  = [[Phil Bryant]]\n|successor    = \n|office2      = 32nd [[Lieutenant Governor of Mississippi]]\n|governor2    = Phil Bryant\n|term_start2  = January 10, 2012\n|term_end2    = January 14, 2020\n|predecessor2 = Phil Bryant\n|successor2   = Delbert Hosemann\n|office3      = 53rd [[Mississippi State Treasurer|Treasurer of Mississippi]]\n|governor3    = [[Haley Barbour]]\n|term_start3  = January 13, 2004\n|term_end3    = January 10, 2012\n|predecessor3 = Peyton Prospere\n|successor3   = [[Lynn Fitch]]\n|birth_name   = Jonathon Tate Reeves\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1974|6|5}}\n|birth_place  = [[Florence, Mississippi]], [[U.S.]]\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = {{marriage|Elee Williams|November 24, 2001}}<ref>https://twitter.com/tatereeves/status/1198712273386250242</ref>\n|children     = 3\n|residence    = [[Mississippi Governor's Mansion|Governor's Mansion]]\n|education    = [[Millsaps College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n|website      = {{url|https://www.ms.gov/node/73|Government website}}\n}}\n\n'''Jonathon Tate Reeves''' (born June 5, 1974) is an [[United States|American]] politician who is the [[List of governors of Mississippi|65th]] [[governor of Mississippi]], serving since 2020, and was [[lieutenant governor of Mississippi]] from 2012 to 2020. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he was previously [[Mississippi State Treasurer]].<ref name=\"MISSISSIPPI FREE PRESS 2020\">{{cite web | title=Mississippi Churches, Stores Reopen As Governor Overrides Mayors\u2019 COVID-19 Orders | website=MISSISSIPPI FREE PRESS | date=2020-03-26 | url=https://www.mississippifreepress.com/mississippi-governor-overrides-mayors-covid-19.html | access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> At age 29, he was the youngest state treasurer in the nation when elected in 2003 and the first Republican to ever hold the office in Mississippi.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.treasury.state.ms.us/Biography/|title=Mississippi Treasurer Tate Reeves|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111083738/http://www.treasury.state.ms.us/Biography/|archivedate=January 11, 2012|url-status=dead|accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref> He was the Republican nominee for [[governor of Mississippi]] in the [[2019 Mississippi gubernatorial election|2019 election]]<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|title=As expected, GOP\u2019s Reeves files for Mississippi governor|url=http://msbusiness.com/2019/01/as-expected-gops-reeves-files-for-mississippi-governor/|work=[[Mississippi Business Journal]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=January 3, 2019|accessdate=January 3, 2019}}</ref><ref name=RunoffResults>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Jasmine C.|last2=Andre|first2=Mike|last3=White|first3=Isaac|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2019/08/27/us/elections/results-mississippi-primary-runoff-election.html|title=Mississippi Primary Runoff Election Results|agency=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 27, 2019|accessdate=August 27, 2019}}</ref> and defeated Democratic Attorney General [[Jim Hood]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/politics/2019/11/05/tate-reeves-wins-mississippi-governor-race-defeats-jim-hood/4159647002/ |title=Republican Tate Reeves wins Mississippi governor race |first1=Luke|last1=Ramseth|first2=Giacomo|last2=Balogna|date=2019-11-05 |work=Mississippi Clarion Ledger |access-date=2019-11-06 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nA native of [[Rankin County, Mississippi|Rankin County]], Mississippi, Reeves graduated in 1992 from [[Florence High School (Mississippi)|Florence High School]] in [[Florence, Mississippi|Florence]]. He is an honors graduate of [[Millsaps College]] in [[Jackson, Mississippi|Jackson]], where he earned a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[economics]]. He played one year as a point guard for the Millsaps Majors [[basketball]] team and was a member of [[Kappa Alpha Order]]. Reeves remains involved with Millsaps by serving as a member of the investment policy board for the General Louis Wilson Fund and a member the Advisory Committee of the Else School of Management.\n\n==Early career==\nAfter Millsaps, Reeves pursued a career in banking and finance in Jackson, where he became assistant vice president for [[AmSouth]], formerly the Deposit Guaranty National Bank, and served as a senior investment analyst.<ref name=\"autogenerated5\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tatereeves.com/biography.html |title=Biography of Tate Reeves|website=tatereeves.com|accessdate=July 4, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050816142757/http://www.tatereeves.com/biography.html |archivedate=August 16, 2005 }}</ref>  In 2000, Reeves became an investment officer for Trustmark National Bank in Jackson.\n\nReeves holds the [[Chartered Financial Analyst]] designation and is a member of the CFA Society of Mississippi and the [[CFA Institute]], an investment industry organization. In 1996, he was the recipient of the Mississippi Society of Financial Analysts Award.\n\n==Mississippi state treasurer==\n===Elections===\n====2003 state treasurer campaign====\nReeves entered the 2003 GOP [[primary election]] and faced former transportation commissioner Wayne Burkes of [[Brandon, Mississippi|Brandon]] and [[Mississippi House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Andrew Ketchings]] of [[Natchez, Mississippi|Natchez]]. Reeves ran strongly in GOP strongholds, including [[Lamar County, Mississippi|Lamar]], [[DeSoto County, Mississippi|DeSoto]], and Rankin counties.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}}. In the three-candidate primary, Reeves led with 49% of the vote,<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://docs.newsbank.com/g/GooglePM/BX/lib00105,0FCC31C84D7566BF.html|title=\"Anderson, Reeves out to early leads in treasurer primaries\", The Sun Herald|accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref> and routed Burkes in the primary runoff.<ref name=\"autogenerated6\">{{cite news|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BX&s_site=sunherald&p_multi=BX&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0FD3BC479270A6A2&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM|title=State and County races|work=[[The Sun-Herald|The Sun Herald]]|accessdate=July 4, 2011 | date=August 27, 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Reeves defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] [[Nomination|nominee]] Gary Anderson, the state director of finance and administration, 52% to 48%.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=rMROAAAAIBAJ&sjid=rg4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=6719,3447079&dq=tate+reeves+wins+gary+anderson&hl=en|title=Race may have been factor in Miss. elections|last=Byrd|first=Sheila Hardwell|work=[[The Ocala Star-Banner]] |accessdate=July 4, 2011 | date=November 6, 2003}}</ref>\n\n====2007 treasurer election====\nUnopposed in the GOP primary, Reeves's only Democratic opposition in the 2007 general election was perennial candidate [[Shawn O'Hara]]. Reeves was reelected with 61% of the vote.\n\n===Tenure===\nAs treasurer, Reeves served as president of the National Association of State Treasurers in 2006\u201307. He is a member and former chairman of the Long Range Planning Committee and a member of the Federal Legislative Committee. He was previously a member of the NAST Executive Committee. Reeves represents the State of Mississippi as a member of the Executive Board of the College Savings Plans Network. He serves on the board of trustees for the Public Employees' Retirement System of Mississippi, and is the chairman of the board of directors of College Savings Plans of Mississippi and the Mississippi Health Care Trust Fund.\n\nIn 2007, ''Rising Tide'' magazine, the publication of the [[Republican National Committee]], named Reeves one of 42 national \"Rising Star(s) in the Republican Party\". In 2008, Reeves was elected president of the Mississippi Republican Elected Officials Association. In December 2008, the Aspen Institute's Rodel Fellowships in Public Leadership selected him as one of their \"Top Young Elected Officials\" in its Fourth Class of Aspen-Rodel Fellows. Reeves was recognized by his NAST peers as the recipient of the Jesse M. Unruh Award for his service to the association, the profession, and his state.\n\n==Lieutenant governor of Mississippi==\n===Elections===\n====2011 lieutenant governor campaign====\n\nIn February 2011, Reeves officially launched a campaign for lieutenant governor<ref name=\"autogenerated8\">{{cite news|url=http://www.clarionledger.com/article/20110208/NEWS/102080325/Reeves-launches-campaign-lt-gov-|title=Reeves launches campaign for lt.gov|last=Parker|first=Molly|work=[[The Clarion-Ledger]]|accessdate=July 4, 2011|date=February 6, 2011}}</ref> and held a fundraising lead over his primary opponent, [[Mississippi State Senate]]  [[President pro tempore|President Pro Tempore]] [[William Gardner Hewes|Billy Hewes]] of [[Gulfport, Mississippi|Gulfport]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} A May 2011 poll of likely Republican voters showed Reeves with a 51%\u201318% lead over Hewes.<ref name=\"autogenerated4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/56772731/Tate-Reeves-Billy-Hewes-Poll-052711|title=Memo re Mississippi Statewide Republican Primary Survey|date=May 26, 2011|accessdate=July 4, 2011}}</ref>\nOn August 2, 2011, Reeves defeated Hewes. On November 8, he was elected lieutenant governor, succeeding [[Phil Bryant]], who was elected to his first term as [[governor of Mississippi|governor]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Reeves Wins Race For Miss. Lt. Governor |first= |last= |url=http://www.wapt.com/politics/29718333/detail.html |newspaper=[[WAPT (TV)|WAPT]] |date=November 8, 2011 }}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n====2015 reelection====\n\nReeves won reelection as lieutenant governor on November 3, 2015, defeating three opponents, including state Senator [[Timothy L. Johnson]], a Republican-turned-Democrat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wlox.com/story/30428879/tate-reeves-reelected-as-mississippi-governor|title=Tate Reeves re-elected as Mississippi Lt. Governor|date=November 3, 2015|publisher=[[WLOX]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref> Newspaper reporting on the misuse of statewide public official's campaign funds indicated that Reeves did not misuse these funds. Non-election year expenses were directed toward campaign-related items such as computer databases or political travel.<ref>Mollie Bryant, Geoffrey Sender, & Kate Royals. (March 6, 2016). \"Funds used to buy vehicles, pottery\". ''Clarion Ledger''. (Jackson). p. A15</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nReeves served as lieutenant governor from 2012 to 2020.\n\n==Governor of Mississippi==\n===Elections===\n====2019 campaign for governor====\nReeves ran for [[governor of Mississippi]] in the [[2019 Mississippi gubernatorial election|2019 election]].<ref name=\":0\" /> He opposed Medicaid expansion, which he called \u201cObamacare expansion.\u201d He lives in Flowood.\n\nIn the Republican primary, he and [[Bill Waller Jr.]] finished in first and second place, respectively. Because no candidate won a majority of the total vote, Reeves and Waller proceeded to a [[runoff election]] on August 27, which Reeves won.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.clarionledger.com/story/news/politics/2019/08/07/election-results-mississippi-governor-race-heading-runoff/1899155001/ |title=Tate Reeves, Bill Waller head to runoff for Republican governor primary |last=Bologna |first=Giacomo |date=2019-08-07 |work=Jackson Clarion-Ledger |access-date=2019-08-07 |last2=Ramseth |first2=Luke |language=en}}</ref><ref name=RunoffResults/>\n\n===Tenure===\nReeves was sworn in as governor on January 14, 2020. <ref>https://www.jacksonfreepress.com/news/2020/mar/24/gov-tate-reeves-orders-limited-gatherings-today-ex/</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\n\nIn the midst of the acceleration of the [[Covid-19]] [[pandemic]], Reeves overrode local leaders' decisions to order people to stay at home, instead telling Mississippians get back to \"life as usual\" and deeming places like bars, dine-in restaurants and churches \"essential services\". The decision was widely condemned.<ref>Adam Ganusheau [https://www.sunherald.com/news/politics-government/article241524861.html Mayors scramble to know: Does Gov. Reeves\u2019 coronavirus declaration clash with local orders?] March 26, 2020 ''[[Mississippi Today]]'' via ''[[Sun Herald]]''</ref> On April 3, Reeves\u2019s Shelter in Place Order 1466 went into effect at 5pm.[https://www.sos.ms.gov/Education-Publications/ExecutiveOrders/1466.pdf order 1466]\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Treasurer Republican Primary Election, 2003\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves'''\n|80,770\n|48.48\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Wayne Burkes'''\n|51,745\n|31.06\n|-\n|Republican\n|Andrew Ketchings\n|33,795\n|20.28\n|-\n|Republican\n|Write-ins\n|311\n|0.19\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Treasurer Republican Primary Election Runoff, 2003\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|-\n|Republican\n|'''Tate Reeves'''\n|49,466\n|72.16\n|-\n|Republican\n|Wayne Burkes\n|19,047\n|27.78\n|-\n|Republican\n|Write-ins\n|39\n|0.06\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"4\" |Mississippi Treasurer Election, 2003\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|